The problem:
Building a successful product is hard. Building a successful product in web3 is borderline absurd. As a founder/dev you have to:
+ create something that works
+ create something that users like
+ create something that is meta specific
+ create something FAST because the meta has already changed to donkey poops
+ create a way to improve your product every week because "WEB3 time passes differently, bro"
+ create a way to keep providing value to your users (meaning making them richer)
+ DON'T CREATE A PONZI
+ be available in discord all the time to support your community
+ make sure you refund all the "investoooors" because it's always your fault for their struggles
+ meet deadlines (like WEN, it was supposed to be ready yesterday)
+ struggle with a new technology lacking underlying infrastructure
+ SLEEP WELL, KNOWING THAT MILLIONS OF USER FUNDS CAN BE LOST BECAUSE OF A HACK OR CARELESS DEV ERROR

Now consider being a dev/founder coming from the web2 world. Usually, a web2 product takes years to develop and goes through countless iterations. 

Devs have time to:
+ plan features
+ implement them
+ run tests on them
+ gather feedback before releasing
+ release and iterate by fixing the issues

IN NONE OF THE ABOVE, do you have users complaining about them not being rich because you are slow or incompetent.

I personally have been in product design for more than 15 years, have been a part of 5+ early-stage startups, and have been advising others on how to ship and iterate fast. I came to web3 with the mindset of a "veteran" in agile and feeling confident that the speed of crypto is something I could tackle. Three years later, I was burned out and gave up dev/founder work for good. It's simply too stressful and unrewarding regarding what you get in return. It may be that the products I've worked on suck, but I mostly felt disappointed by the lack of support and understanding of "degens" and their "WEN" mentality. MFRS never coded a single line in their lives but suddenly talked about deadlines, UX, bugs, value proposition, community management, support level, etc. Fuck that. I'm done. Anyway, back to the French Tech.

Have @travisbickle0x and the team got what it takes?
+ They ship fast
+ They iterate fast
+ They are cool with pivoting to the things that work/make sense
+ They listen to the community feedback and try to act upon it
+ They are fearless when it comes to big things - examples: v2 was a big big thing, a nightmare for any dev team to migrate to a completely new UX/UI, Going cross-chain, allowing for Sybils to stress test the free version, having 2 separate app versions (they differ in many ways)
+ They care about the users - although it feels like sometimes the "support" is missing
+ They don't have a robust testing infrastructure - many bugs and things not working since day one, BUT everything eventually works
+ They have the Fantardio mentality - not giving a shit about non-constructive feedback
+ They shit-post a lot - nuking the sybils by changing cards to Mikado and @0xKipit 

This is the only way to survive in a TENSE environment where sentiment aligns with how the coin charts are skewed. I am done, but I hope they survive this harsh environment.

Lastly, My thoughts on Monad Testnet:
+ it is NOT a new version of the app
+ IT IS a stress test on the system (API, infra, support, etc.)
+ IT IS going multi-chain (investors love this)
+ IT IS a new business model - Monad wants a stress test on their new L1 - fantasy provides this for the exchange of airdrop for testers - WIN WIN WIN
+ The next L1 wants this stress test - ok, let's change the color of the app and put a new logo on the packs
+ What happens when Monad launches - well, it becomes Monad mainnet fantasy - with a LOT of cards in circulation and a LOT of users - prices of the cards will be adjusted to that number - there is your low-cost entry to the ecosystem

Thanks for your attention, Chosta out.
